{"title_page": "Eureka, Nunavut", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name = Eureka\n|other_name =\n|native_name =<!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname =\n|settlement_type = Settlement<!--For Town or Village (Leave blank for the default City)-->\n|motto =\n|image_skyline = Eureka Weather Station 1997-08-04.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|image_caption = Eureka seen from its airfield\n|image_flag =\n|flag_size =\n|image_seal =\n|seal_size =\n|image_shield =\n|shield_size =\n|pushpin_map = Canada Nunavut#Canada\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name = Canada\n|subdivision_type1 = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Territory]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Nunavut]]\n|subdivision_type2 = Region\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Qikiqtaaluk Region]]\n|subdivision_type3 = Island group\n|subdivision_name3 = [[Queen Elizabeth Islands]]\n|subdivision_type4 =\n|subdivision_name4 =\n|government_footnotes =\n|government_type =\n|leader_title =\n|leader_name =\n|leader_title1 = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1 =\n|leader_title2 =\n|leader_name2 =\n|leader_title3 =\n|leader_name3 =\n|leader_title4 =\n|leader_name4 =\n|established_title = Founded\n|established_date = April 11, 1947\n|established_title2 = <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2 =\n|established_title3 = <!-- Incorporated (city) -->\n|established_date3 =\n|area_magnitude =\n|unit_pref =<!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes =\n|area_total_km2 =<!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_land_km2 =<!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n|area_water_km2 =\n|area_total_sq_mi =\n|area_land_sq_mi =\n|area_water_sq_mi =\n|area_water_percent =\n|area_urban_km2 =\n|area_urban_sq_mi =\n|area_metro_km2 =\n|area_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_as_of =\n|population_footnotes =\n|population_note =\n|population_total = 8<ref name=welcome/>\n|population_density_km2 =\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n|population_metro =\n|population_density_metro_km2 =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_urban =\n|population_density_urban_km2 =\n|population_density_urban_sq_mi =\n|population_blank1_title =\n|population_blank1 =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =\n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n|timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]<ref name=welcome/>\n|utc_offset = \u221205:00\n|coordinates = {{coord|79|59|20|N|085|56|27|W|region:CA-NU_type:city_scale:20000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes =<ref name=cfs>{{CFS}}</ref>\n|elevation_m =\n|elevation_ft = 272\n|postal_code_type = Postal code\n|postal_code =X0A 0G0<ref name=welcome/>\n|area_code =613<ref name=welcome/><ref name=code/>\n|blank_name =\n|blank_info =\n|blank1_name =\n|blank1_info =\n|website =\n|footnotes = Population consists of 6 [[Meteorological Service of Canada|MSC]] staff and 2 contracted employees<ref name=welcome/> Elevation is at [[Eureka Aerodrome]].\n}}\n\n'''Eureka''' is a small research base on [[Fosheim Peninsula]], [[Ellesmere Island]], [[Qikiqtaaluk Region]], in the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian territory]] of [[Nunavut]]. It is located on the north side of Slidre Fiord, which enters [[Eureka Sound]] farther west. It is the third-northernmost permanent research community in the world.  The only two farther north are [[Alert, Nunavut|Alert]], which is also on Ellesmere Island, and [[Nord, Greenland|Nord]], in [[Greenland]].  Eureka has the lowest average annual temperature and the lowest amount of precipitation of any weather station in Canada.<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/cold-places-in-canada/ Cold Places in Canada]</ref>{{fv|date=February 2016}}\n\nEureka's [[Canadian postal code|postal code]] is X0A 0G0 and the [[Telephone numbering plan|area code]] is [[Area code 613|613]].<ref name=\"welcome\">[https://wattsupwiththat.files.wordpress.com/2010/04/visitor_guide_to_eureka_apr_2010.pdf Welcome to the Eureka Weather Station]</ref><ref name=code>[http://lupit.nunavut.ca/app/dms/script/dms_download.php?fileid=13635&applicationid=148746&sessionid=90f8a3mku1bsrt5hp4g7o4n9q2 Emergency Plan for Storage Tank Systems of Petroleum and Allied Petroleum Products at Eureka High Arctic Weather Station]</ref>\n\n==Divisions==\nThe base consists of three areas:{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n*the [[Eureka Aerodrome]] which includes \"Fort Eureka\" (the quarters for military personnel maintaining the island's communications equipment)\n*the [[Environment Canada]] Weather Station\n*the [[Polar Environment Atmospheric Research Laboratory]] (PEARL), formerly the Arctic Stratospheric Ozone Observatory (AStrO)<ref>[http://www.candac.ca/candac/Facilities/facility.php?type=PEARL Polar Environment Atmospheric Research Laboratory]</ref>\n\nPEARL is operated by a consortium of Canadian university researchers and government agencies known as the Canadian Network for Detection of Atmospheric Change.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.candac.ca|title=CANDAC|publisher=}}</ref> PEARL announced it would cease full-time year-round operation as of April 30, 2012, due to lack of funding, but this decision was reversed in May 2013 with the announcement of new funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/high-arctic-research-station-saved-by-new-funding-1.1360779|title=High Arctic research station saved by new funding|date=17 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nEureka was founded on April 11, 1947, as part of a requirement to set up a network of Arctic [[weather station]]s. On this date, {{convert|100|t}} of supplies were airlifted to a promising spot on Ellesmere Island, and five prefabricated [[Jamesway hut]]s were constructed. Regular weather observations began on January 1, 1948. The station has expanded over the years. At its peak, in the 1970s, at least fifteen staff were on site; in 2005, it reported a permanent population of zero with at least 8 staff on a continuous rotational basis.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nSeveral generations of buildings have been developed. The latest operations centre, with work areas and staff quarters in one large structure, was completed in 2005.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n==Climate==\nEureka experiences a [[polar climate]] (''ET''). The settlement sees the [[midnight sun]] between April 10 and August 29, with no sunlight at all between mid-October and late February. Eureka has the lowest average annual temperature and least precipitation of any weather station in Canada with an annual mean temperature of {{convert|-18.8|\u00b0C}}. However, summers are slightly warmer than other places in the [[Canadian Arctic Archipelago|Canadian Arctic]] because Eureka is somewhat landlocked, being near the centre of [[Ellesmere Island]]. Even so, since record keeping began, the temperature has never exceeded {{convert|20.9|\u00b0C}}, first reached on July 14, 2009.<ref name=\"Eureka A\"/> Although a polar desert, evaporation is also very low, which allows the limited moisture to be made available for plants and wildlife.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Eureka, 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1947\u2013present{{efn|Record humidex 23.0 for January is an error and should not be entered.}}\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan maximum humidex= \n|Feb maximum humidex= -1.1\n|Mar maximum humidex= -8.5\n|Apr maximum humidex= -3.0\n|May maximum humidex= 7.3\n|Jun maximum humidex= 17.9\n|Jul maximum humidex= 20.8\n|Aug maximum humidex= 16.3\n|Sep maximum humidex= 7.2\n|Oct maximum humidex= 4.8\n|Nov maximum humidex= -3.9\n|Dec maximum humidex= -4.0\n|year maximum humidex= 23.0\n|Jan record high C = -1.1\n|Feb record high C = -1.1\n|Mar record high C = -8.0\n|Apr record high C = -2.8\n|May record high C = 7.5\n|Jun record high C = 18.5\n|Jul record high C = 20.9\n|Aug record high C = 1