43e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442<ref name=\"climate\">\u2014[http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/climate/24266.htm \u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442]. Retrieved January 1, 2013.</ref>{{Self-published source|date=February 2017}}January record<ref>Verkhoyansk Monument image: https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-JZsosJzSVV8/WJv6EuE-_QI/AAAAAAABRs0/BRgPwLTin-4/verkhoyansk-87.jpg?imgmax=1600</ref>\n|source 2 = NOAA (precipitation days and sunshine hours, 1961-1990)<ref name =\"climate2\">{{cite web|url=ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REG_II/RA/24266.TXT |title=Verhojansk Climate Normals 1961\u20131990 |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] | accessdate=February 9, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*Official website of the Sakha Republic. ''Registry of the Administrative-Territorial Divisions of the Sakha Republic''. [https://web.archive.org/web/20131113122109/http://sakha.gov.ru/node/12523 Verkhoyansky District]. {{in lang|ru}}\n*{{RussiaAdmMunRef|sa|mun|list1}}\n\n{{Sakha Republic}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in the Sakha Republic]]\n[[Category:Populated places of Arctic Russia]]\n[[Category:Weather extremes of Earth]]\n", "name_user": "24.68.2.110", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(It also boarders on a Dwd due to drier winters)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verkhoyansk"}
{"title_page": "Oymyakon", "text_new": "{{Infobox Russian rural locality\n|en_name=Oymyakon\n|ru_name=\u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\n|loc_name1=\u04e8\u0439\u043c\u04e9\u043a\u04e9\u04e9\u043d\n|loc_lang1=Yakut\n|image_skyline=Oymyakon_-_190228_DSC_5642.jpg\n|image_caption=\n|map_label_position=right\n|coordinates = {{coord|63|27|39|N|142|47|09|E|display=inline,title}}\n|federal_subject=[[Sakha Republic]]\n|federal_subject_ref=\n|adm_data_as_of=\n|adm_district_jur=[[Oymyakonsky District]]\n|adm_district_jur_ref=\n|adm_ctr_of=\n|adm_ctr_of_ref=\n|inhabloc_cat=Rural locality\n|inhabloc_cat_ref=\n|inhabloc_type=''[[Village#Russia|Selo]]''\n|inhabloc_type_ref=\n|mun_data_as_of=\n|mun_district_jur=Oymyakonsky Municipal District\n|urban_settlement_jur=\n|urban_settlement_jur_ref=\n|rural_settlement_jur=\n|rural_settlement_jur_ref=\n|inter_settlement_territory=\n|inter_settlement_territory_ref=\n|mun_admctr_of=\n|mun_admctr_of_ref=\n|area_of_what=\n|area_as_of=\n|area_km2=\n|area_km2_ref=\n|pop_2010census= 462\n|pop_2010census_rank= \n|pop_2010census_ref=<ref name=\"PopCensus\">{{ru-pop-ref|2010Census}}</ref>\n|pop_density=\n|pop_density_as_of=\n|pop_density_ref=\n|pop_latest=500\u2013900\n|pop_latest_date=February 5, 2018\n|pop_latest_ref=<ref name=\"Konbini\" group=Videos>{{cite web |title=Visite du village le plus froid du monde |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylpuGUWGdSs |website=YouTube |publisher=Konbini News |accessdate=27 October 2018 |date=5 February 2018 |language=fr}}</ref>\n|established_date=\n|established_title=\n|established_date_ref=\n|current_cat_date=\n|current_cat_date_ref=\n|prev_name1=\n|prev_name1_date=\n|prev_name1_ref=\n|postal_codes=678752\n|postal_codes_ref=\n|dialing_codes=41154\n|dialing_codes_ref=\n|website=\n|website_ref=\n|commonscat=\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n'''Oymyakon''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u0301\u043d}}, {{IPA-ru|\u0250jm\u02b2\u026a\u02c8kon|pron}}; {{lang-sah|\u04e8\u0439\u043c\u04e9\u043a\u04e9\u04e9\u043d}}, ''\u00d6ym\u00f6k\u00f6\u00f6n'', {{IPA-all|\u00f8jm\u00f8\u02c8k\u00f8\u02d0n}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a ''[[village#Russia|selo]]'') in [[Oymyakonsky District]] of the [[Sakha Republic]], [[Russia]], located along the [[Indigirka River]], {{convert|30|km|sp=us}} northwest of [[Tomtor, Oymyakonsky District, Sakha Republic|Tomtor]] on the [[M56 Kolyma Highway|Kolyma Highway]]. It is one of the coldest permanently inhabited settlements on Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inspiremore.com/worlds-coldest-village/|title=World's Coldest Village Drops To -80\u00b0 & The Photos Are Spectacular.|date=January 16, 2018|website=InspireMore.com|access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nIt is named after the Oymyakon River, whose name reportedly comes from the [[Even language|Even]] word ''kheium'', meaning \"unfrozen patch of water; place where fish spend the winter\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Pospelov|first=Evgeniy Mikhaylovich|script-title=ru:\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430|location=Moscow|year=1998|p=307|language=Russian}}</ref> However, another source states that the Even word ''heyum'' (h\u044dj\u0443\u043c) (''kheium'' may be a misspelling) means \"frozen lake\".<ref>{{citation |last=Tsintsius |first=V. I. |publisher=Nauka |year=1977 |volume=2 |page=361 |publication-place=Leningrad |script-title=ru:\u0421\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c \u0442\u0443\u043d\u0433\u0443\u0441\u043e-\u043c\u0430\u043d\u044c\u0447\u0436\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u043e\u0432 : \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b \u043a \u044d\u0442\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044e|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nOymyakon has two main valleys beside it. These valleys trap wind inside the town and create the colder climate. The temperatures here are extremely cold throughout the year, and it snows frequently. Schools are closed if it is colder than {{convert|\u221255.0|C|1}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l1noUh2NrLI&t=738|title=Visiting the coldest town in the world - Chilling Out - 60 Minutes Australia|date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDuring [[World War II]], an airfield was built for the Alaska-Siberian ([[ALSIB]]) air route, used to ferry American [[Lend-Lease]] aircraft to the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Lebedev|first=Igor|title=Aviation Lend-Lease to Russia|publisher=Nova Publishers|year=1997|pp=44\u201349}}</ref>\n\nOver the last few decades, the population of Oymyakon has shrunk significantly. The village had a peak population of roughly 2,500 inhabitants, but that number has decreased to fewer than 900 in 2018.<ref name=\"Konbini\" group=Videos />\n\n==Climate==\nWith an extreme [[subarctic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Dfd/Dwd''), Oymyakon is known as one of the places considered the Northern [[Pole of Cold]], the other being the [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|town]] of [[Verkhoyansk]], located {{cvt|629|km|mi}} away by air. The ground is permanently frozen (continuous [[permafrost]]).\n\nThere is a monument built around the town square commemorating a reading in January 1924 of {{convert|\u221271.2|C|1}}. This was shown on the Australian program ''[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]]'' in a 2012 documentary.<ref name=\"60 Min Australia\">{{cite web |title=Chilling Out \u2013 Visiting the Coldest Town in the World |work=[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]] |date=20 June 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l1noUh2NrLI |via=[[YouTube]] }}</ref> On February 6, 1933, a temperature of {{convert|\u221267.7|C|1}} was recorded at Oymyakon's weather station.<ref name=\"Stepanova\">{{cite web|author=N.A. Stepanova |title=On the Lowest Temperatures on Earth|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/086/mwr-086-01-0006.pdf |publisher=Docs.lib.noaa.gov\n|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193535/http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/086/mwr-086-01-0006.pdf|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher C. Burt|title=The Coldest Places on Earth|website=Weather Underground |url=https://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/the-coldest-places-on-earth |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319233430/https://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/the-coldest-places-on-earth|archive-date=March 19, 2016}}</ref> This was the coldest officially recorded temperature in the [[Northern Hemisphere]]. Only [[Antarctica]] has recorded lower official temperatures (the lowest being {{convert|-89.2|C|F}}, recorded at [[Vostok Station]] on 21 July 1983).<ref>{{cite web|title=World:Lowest Temperature |url=http://wmo.asu.edu/world-lowest-temperature |publisher=[[World Meteorological Organization]] |accessdate=February 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616025722/http://wmo.asu.edu/world-lowest-temperature |archivedate=16 June 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Global Weather & Climate Extremes|url=http://wmo.asu.edu/#global|publisher=World Meteorological Organization|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref> Therefore, Russia can be said to hold both the coldest temperatures in the Northern and Southern Hemispheres.\n\nThe weather station is in a valley between Oymyakon and [[Tomtor, Oymyakonsky District, Sakha Republic|Tomtor]]. The station is at {{cvt|750|m|ft}} above [[sea level]] and the surrounding mountains at {{cvt|1100|m|ft}}, causing cold air to pool in the valley: in fact, recent studies show that winter temperatures in the area ''increase'' with altitude by as much as {{convert|10|C-change}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igsoc.org/annals/v52/58/a58A068.pdf |title=International Glaciological Society (IGS) |publisher=Igsoc.org |date=2012-02-13 |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome years the temperature drops below {{convert|0|C|0}} in late September and may remain below freezing until mid-April. In Oymyakon sometimes the average minimum temperature for December, January, and February remains below {{convert|-50|C|0}}. Sometimes summer months can also be quite cold, but June and July are the only months where the temperature has never dropped below {{convert|-10|C|0}}. Oymyakon and Verkhoyansk are the only two permanently inhabited places in the world that have recorded temperatures below {{convert|-60.0|C|0}} for every day in January.<ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24688&month=1&year=2013 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"climate-verkhoyansk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24266&month=1&year=2013 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435 |publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOymyakon has never recorded an above-freezing temperature between October 25 and March 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24688&month=10&year=2013 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough winters in Oymyakon are long and extremely cold, summers are mild to warm, sometimes hot.\nThe warmest month on record is July 2010 with an average temperature of {{convert|+18.7|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24688&month=7&year=2010|title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogoda.ru.net |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> In June, July and August temperatures over {{convert|30|C|0}} are not rare during the day. On July 28,&nbsp;2010, Oymyakon recorded a record high temperature of {{convert|34.6|C|0}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pogoda.ru.net/monitor.php?id=24688&month=7&year=2010 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogoda.ru.net |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> yielding a temperature range of {{convert|102.3|C-change}}. [[Verkhoyansk]] and [[Yakutsk]] are the only other known places in the world that have a temperature amplitude higher than {{convert|100|C-change}}.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nThe climate is quite dry, but as average monthly temperatures are below freezing for seven months of the year, substantial evaporation occurs only in summer months. Summers are much wetter than winters.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location=Oymyakon (1981\u20132010), extremes 1891\u2013present\n|metric first= yes\n|single line=yes\n|Jan record high C = \u221216.6\n|Feb record high C = \u221212.5\n|Mar record high C = 2.0\n|Apr record high C = 11.7\n|May record high C = 26.2\n|Jun record high C = 31.1\n|Jul record high C = 34.6\n|Aug record high C = 33.1\n|Sep record high C = 23.7\n|Oct record high C = 11.0\n|Nov record high C = \u22122.1\n|Dec record high C = \u22126.5\n|year record high C = 34.6\n|Jan high C = \u221243.0\n|Feb high C = \u221235.7\n|Mar high C = \u221220.8\n|Apr high C = \u22123.7\n|May high C = 9.1\n|Jun high C = 20.0\n|Jul high C = 22.7\n|Aug high C = 18.1\n|Sep high C = 8.9\n|Oct high C = \u22129.2\n|Nov high C = \u221231.0\n|Dec high C = \u221242.4\n|year high C = \u22128.9\n|Jan mean C = \u221246.4\n|Feb mean C = \u221242.0\n|Mar mean C = \u221231.2\n|Apr mean C = \u221213.6\n|May mean C = 2.7\n|Jun mean C = 12.6\n|Jul mean C = 14.9\n|Aug mean C = 10.3\n|Sep mean C = 2.3\n|Oct mean C = \u221214.8\n|Nov mean C = \u221235.2\n|Dec mean C = \u221245.5\n|year mean C = \u221215.5\n|Jan low C = \u221250.0\n|Feb low C = \u221247.3\n|Mar low C = \u221240.0\n|Apr low C = \u221223.9\n|May low C = \u22124.6\n|Jun low C = 4.0\n|Jul low C = 6.2\n|Aug low C = 2.5\n|Sep low C = \u22123.7\n|Oct low C = \u221220.4\n|Nov low C = \u221239.6\n|Dec low C = \u221248.8\n|year low C = \u221222.1\n|Jan record low C = \u221265.4\n|Feb record low C = \u221267.7 <!-- This record comes from the WMO record page (source labeled \"February record low\" below) and was recorded in 1933. The main source http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/ does not include records before about 1943, but the -67.7C is valid. Please consult the talk page before changing this figure. -->\n|Mar record low C = \u221260.6\n|Apr record low C = \u221246.4\n|May record low C = \u221228.9\n|Jun record low C = \u22129.7\n|Jul record low C = \u22129.3\n|Aug record low C = \u221217.1\n|Sep record low C = \u221225.3\n|Oct record low C = \u221247.6\n|Nov record low C = \u221258.5\n|Dec record low C = -62.8\n|Jan precipitation mm = 6\n|Feb precipitation mm = 7\n|Mar precipitation mm = 5\n|Apr precipitation mm = 6\n|May precipitation mm = 13\n|Jun precipitation mm = 34\n|Jul precipitation mm = 45\n|Aug precipitation mm = 39\n|Sep precipitation mm = 23\n|Oct precipitation mm = 14\n|Nov precipitation mm = 12\n|Dec precipitation mm = 8\n|year precipitation mm = 215\n|unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n|Jan precipitation days = 3.0\n|Feb precipitation days = 2.6\n|Mar precipitation days = 1.4\n|Apr precipitation days = 1.8\n|May precipitation days = 3.2\n|Jun precipitation days = 6.6\n|Jul precipitation days = 8.7\n|Aug precipitation days = 7.7\n|Sep precipitation days = 5.1\n|Oct precipitation days = 4.9\n|Nov precipitation days = 4.0\n|Dec precipitation days = 3.0\n|year precipitation days = 52.0\n| Jan rain days  =0\n| Feb rain days  =0\n| Mar rain days  =0\n| Apr rain days  =0\n| May rain days  =10\n| Jun rain days  =17\n| Jul rain days  =17\n| Aug rain days  =18\n| Sep rain days  =13\n| Oct rain days  =1\n| Nov rain days  =0\n| Dec rain days  =0\n| year rain days =76\n| Jan snow days  =23\n| Feb snow days  =23\n| Mar snow days  =16\n| Apr snow days  =10\n| May snow days  =9\n| Jun snow days  =1\n| Jul snow days  =0\n| Aug snow days  =0\n| Sep snow days  =9\n| Oct snow days  =21\n| Nov snow days  =23\n| Dec snow days  =20\n| year snow days =156\n|Jan humidity = 75\n|Feb humidity = 74\n|Mar humidity = 72\n|Apr humidity = 68\n|May humidity = 60\n|Jun humidity = 59\n|Jul humidity = 65\n|Aug humidity = 70\n|Sep humidity = 73\n|Oct humidity = 79 \n|Nov humidity = 77\n|Dec humidity = 74\n|year humidity = 71\n|Jan sun = 28\n|Feb sun = 118\n|Mar sun = 244\n|Apr sun = 284\n|May sun = 282\n|Jun sun = 304\n|Jul sun = 298\n|Aug sun = 236\n|Sep sun = 151\n|Oct sun = 113\n|Nov sun = 58\n|Dec sun = 13\n|year sun = 2129\n|source 1 = \u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442,<ref name=\"climatebox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/climate/24688.htm |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0430 |publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru |date= |accessdate=2017-02-16}}</ref><sup>February record low</sup><ref name=\"wmo\">{{cite web |url= http://wmo.asu.edu/asia-lowest-temperature |title= Asia: Lowest Temperature |publisher= [[WMO]] |accessdate= June 19, 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100616051245/http://wmo.asu.edu/asia-lowest-temperature |archivedate= June 16, 2010 |df= mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435. \u0422\u0435\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0445\u0430 \u0438 \u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0438. \u0424\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c 2014 \u0433.|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24688|publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru|accessdate=February 10, 2014}}</ref> \n|source 2 = NOAA (precipitation days and sunshine hours)<ref name=\"climate2\">{{cite web|url=ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REG_II/RA/24688.TXT |title=Ojmjakon Climate Normals 1961\u20131990 |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] | accessdate = February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:Oymyakon forests.jpg|thumb|Landscape near Oymyakon in February 2013]]\n\n==In the media==\nOymyakon has been featured in a number of television series:\n* The episode \"The Winter's Tale\" of the 1996 [[PBS]] weather documentary series ''Savage Skies''.\n* The season two episode \"Siberia\" of the documentary series ''[[World's Most Dangerous Roads]]''.\n* [[Oxford]] geographer [[Nick Middleton]]'s television series and accompanying book ''Going to Extremes'', in which he discusses his visit to this village and describes ways in which inhabitants cope with the extreme cold.  Middleton describes how Oymyakon lies between two mountain ranges, trapping cold air between throughout the year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bijal P. Trivedi|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/05/0512_040512_tvoymyakon.html |title=Life Is a Chilling Challenge in Subzero Siberia |website=National Geographic Channel|date=May 12, 2004}}</ref> In the winter, once every two days, the village's cattle's [[herd bull]] was harnessed between the shafts of a sledge with a big water tank on it and led to the spring. The men broke the ice on the spring, let the bull drink its fill, filled the water tank from the spring, and let the bull pull the tanker sledge back into the warm. The water spring was naturally warm and so stayed liquid below the surface ice.\n* Cameraman Geoff Mackley along with Rachael Wilson and Mark Whetu from New Zealand, made an episode for [[Discovery Channel]] series Dangerman. They were accompanied by translator Rob Walker (USA) and Vyacheslav Ipatiev (TourServiceCenter). Geoff rode the bull which pulled the water tank sledge to the spring, and spent a night outside in a tent.<ref name=\"RamboCam\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.rambocam.com/archive/siberia.html |title=Geoff Mackley \u2013 Siberia \u2013 Oymyakon expedition Jan 2004 |publisher=Rambocam.com |date=January 29, 2004 |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Yakutia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.yakutiatravel.com/eng/whatson1.htm |title=Events 2005\u20132010 &#124; Sakha Yakutia \u2013 Heart of Siberia |publisher=Yakutiatravel.com |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* The episode \"Hot and Cold\" in the 2010 BBC series ''Extreme World'' features the village.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-11840494 | work=BBC News | title=Extreme world \u2013 How great are the world's divides? | date=November 25, 2010}}</ref>\n* The episode \"Chilling Out\" in the 1 April 2012 Episode of Australia's ''60 Minutes''.<ref name=\"60 Min Australia\" />\n* The travel series ''[[Departures (TV series)|Departures]]'', season 3, episode 2: \"Russia: The Bull of Winter\", March 13, 2010. Travelers Scott Wilson and Justin Lukach, Director of Photography/Director Andre Dupuis, Translator Bogdan Almazov.<ref name=\"departures \">{{cite web | url=http://www.departuresentertainment.com/episode_s3_ep1-ep5.html | title=Episode Guide | publisher=Departureentertainment.coms | accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref>\n* \"Coldest Road\", an episode of the [[Discovery Channel]] three-part series ''Driven to Extremes'' starring [[Tom Hardy]].\n* The TV show ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]'' episode \"Dead Red\" talked about sending a Russian diplomat there to serve his time for a crime he committed.\n* In the television show ''[[Angry Planet]]'' with [[George Kourounis]], episode \u201cMelting [[Siberia]]\u201d, the city and region are explored in relation to melting [[permafrost]] and [[climate change]].\n* German meteorologist Sebastian Balders traveled to Oymyakon in December 2014 and shot [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3KInXvWoq9U&t=86s a documentary about his trip] and about the village. He published it on [[YouTube]] with very rare video material. According to Oymyakon's mayor, Balders was the youngest tourist ever at the age of just 23.\n* The episode 18 \"Secret War\" of ''[[Love, Death & Robots]]'' takes place in Oymyakon region.\n* \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5HXXJg4vDF8 Most dangerous ways to school \u2013 OIMJAKON (Russia)]\" is a documentary on how children survive their trek to school, juxtaposed with video detailing how the people survive in general.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Verkhoyansk]], another candidate for the \"Northern [[Pole of Cold]]\"\n*[[Yakutsk]], coldest major city\n*[[Summit Camp]]\n*[[Eismitte]]\n*[[Oymyakon Plateau]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Videos===\n{{Reflist|group=Videos}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage}}\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.somerikko.net/travel/oymyakon.html Oymyakon 1996/97 Expedition]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101123092218/http://oymyakon2008.webs.com/ 2008/09 Expedition]\n*[http://www.wr-presse.de/Download/city_map_oymyakon.pdf City map Oymyakon]\n*[http://www.educatedearth.net/video.php?id=3958 Video report from SkyNews]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090829144424/http://askyakutia.com/tag/oymyakon/ Life in Oymyakon. AskYakutia.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121116062522/http://www.departuresentertainment.com/about.html Russia: The Bull of Winter Season 3 Episode 2 Departures]\n*[http://www.yakutiatravel.com/the-pole-of-cold/oymyakon-general-information.html/ General information about Oymyakon]\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in the Sakha Republic]]\n[[Category:Weather extremes of Earth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Russian rural locality\n|en_name=Oymyakon\n|ru_name=\u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\n|loc_name1=\u04e8\u0439\u043c\u04e9\u043a\u04e9\u04e9\u043d\n|loc_lang1=Yakut\n|image_skyline=Oymyakon_-_190228_DSC_5642.jpg\n|image_caption=\n|map_label_position=right\n|coordinates = {{coord|63|27|39|N|142|47|09|E|display=inline,title}}\n|federal_subject=[[Sakha Republic]]\n|federal_subject_ref=\n|adm_data_as_of=\n|adm_district_jur=[[Oymyakonsky District]]\n|adm_district_jur_ref=\n|adm_ctr_of=\n|adm_ctr_of_ref=\n|inhabloc_cat=Rural locality\n|inhabloc_cat_ref=\n|inhabloc_type=''[[Village#Russia|Selo]]''\n|inhabloc_type_ref=\n|mun_data_as_of=\n|mun_district_jur=Oymyakonsky Municipal District\n|urban_settlement_jur=\n|urban_settlement_jur_ref=\n|rural_settlement_jur=\n|rural_settlement_jur_ref=\n|inter_settlement_territory=\n|inter_settlement_territory_ref=\n|mun_admctr_of=\n|mun_admctr_of_ref=\n|area_of_what=\n|area_as_of=\n|area_km2=\n|area_km2_ref=\n|pop_2010census= 462\n|pop_2010census_rank= \n|pop_2010census_ref=<ref name=\"PopCensus\">{{ru-pop-ref|2010Census}}</ref>\n|pop_density=\n|pop_density_as_of=\n|pop_density_ref=\n|pop_latest=500\u2013900\n|pop_latest_date=February 5, 2018\n|pop_latest_ref=<ref name=\"Konbini\" group=Videos>{{cite web |title=Visite du village le plus froid du monde |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylpuGUWGdSs |website=YouTube |publisher=Konbini News |accessdate=27 October 2018 |date=5 February 2018 |language=fr}}</ref>\n|established_date=\n|established_title=\n|established_date_ref=\n|current_cat_date=\n|current_cat_date_ref=\n|prev_name1=\n|prev_name1_date=\n|prev_name1_ref=\n|postal_codes=678752\n|postal_codes_ref=\n|dialing_codes=41154\n|dialing_codes_ref=\n|website=\n|website_ref=\n|commonscat=\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n'''Oymyakon''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u0301\u043d}}, {{IPA-ru|\u0250jm\u02b2\u026a\u02c8kon|pron}}; {{lang-sah|\u04e8\u0439\u043c\u04e9\u043a\u04e9\u04e9\u043d}}, ''\u00d6ym\u00f6k\u00f6\u00f6n'', {{IPA-all|\u00f8jm\u00f8\u02c8k\u00f8\u02d0n}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a ''[[village#Russia|selo]]'') in [[Oymyakonsky District]] of the [[Sakha Republic]], [[Russia]], located along the [[Indigirka River]], {{convert|30|km|sp=us}} northwest of [[Tomtor, Oymyakonsky District, Sakha Republic|Tomtor]] on the [[M56 Kolyma Highway|Kolyma Highway]]. It is one of the coldest permanently inhabited settlements on Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inspiremore.com/worlds-coldest-village/|title=World's Coldest Village Drops To -80\u00b0 & The Photos Are Spectacular.|date=January 16, 2018|website=InspireMore.com|access-date=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nIt is named after the Oymyakon River, whose name reportedly comes from the [[Even language|Even]] word ''kheium'', meaning \"unfrozen patch of water; place where fish spend the winter\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Pospelov|first=Evgeniy Mikhaylovich|script-title=ru:\u0413\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430|location=Moscow|year=1998|p=307|language=Russian}}</ref> However, another source states that the Even word ''heyum'' (h\u044dj\u0443\u043c) (''kheium'' may be a misspelling) means \"frozen lake\".<ref>{{citation |last=Tsintsius |first=V. I. |publisher=Nauka |year=1977 |volume=2 |page=361 |publication-place=Leningrad |script-title=ru:\u0421\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c \u0442\u0443\u043d\u0433\u0443\u0441\u043e-\u043c\u0430\u043d\u044c\u0447\u0436\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u043e\u0432 : \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b \u043a \u044d\u0442\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044e|language=Russian}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nOymyakon has two main valleys beside it. These valleys trap wind inside the town and create the colder climate. The temperatures here are extremely cold throughout the year, and it snows frequently. Schools are closed if it is colder than {{convert|\u221255.0|C|1}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l1noUh2NrLI&t=738|title=Visiting the coldest town in the world - Chilling Out - 60 Minutes Australia|date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDuring [[World War II]], an airfield was built for the Alaska-Siberian ([[ALSIB]]) air route, used to ferry American [[Lend-Lease]] aircraft to the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Lebedev|first=Igor|title=Aviation Lend-Lease to Russia|publisher=Nova Publishers|year=1997|pp=44\u201349}}</ref>\n\nOver the last few decades, the population of Oymyakon has shrunk significantly. The village had a peak population of roughly 2,500 inhabitants, but that number has decreased to fewer than 900 in 2018.<ref name=\"Konbini\" group=Videos />\n\n==Climate==\nWith an extreme [[subarctic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Dfd/Dwd''), Oymyakon is known as one of the places considered the Northern [[Pole of Cold]], the other being the [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|town]] of [[Verkhoyansk]], located {{cvt|629|km|mi}} away by air. The ground is permanently frozen (continuous [[permafrost]]).\n\nThere is a monument built around the town square commemorating a reading in January 1924 of {{convert|\u221271.2|C|1}}. This was shown on the Australian program ''[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]]'' in a 2012 documentary.<ref name=\"60 Min Australia\">{{cite web |title=Chilling Out \u2013 Visiting the Coldest Town in the World |work=[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]] |date=20 June 2018 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l1noUh2NrLI |via=[[YouTube]] }}</ref> On February 6, 1933, a temperature of {{convert|\u221267.7|C|1}} was recorded at Oymyakon's weather station.<ref name=\"Stepanova\">{{cite web|author=N.A. Stepanova |title=On the Lowest Temperatures on Earth|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/086/mwr-086-01-0006.pdf |publisher=Docs.lib.noaa.gov\n|accessdate=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193535/http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/086/mwr-086-01-0006.pdf|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher C. Burt|title=The Coldest Places on Earth|website=Weather Underground |url=https://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/the-coldest-places-on-earth |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319233430/https://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/the-coldest-places-on-earth|archive-date=March 19, 2016}}</ref> This was the coldest officially recorded temperature in the [[Northern Hemisphere]]. Only [[Antarctica]] has recorded lower official temperatures (the lowest being {{convert|-89.2|C|F}}, recorded at [[Vostok Station]] on 21 July 1983).<ref>{{cite web|title=World:Lowest Temperature |url=http://wmo.asu.edu/world-lowest-temperature |publisher=[[World Meteorological Organization]] |accessdate=February 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616025722/http://wmo.asu.edu/world-lowest-temperature |archivedate=16 June 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Global Weather & Climate Extremes|url=http://wmo.asu.edu/#global|publisher=World Meteorological Organization|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref> Therefore, Russia can be said to hold both the coldest temperatures in the Northern and Southern Hemispheres.\n\nThe weather station is in a valley between Oymyakon and [[Tomtor, Oymyakonsky District, Sakha Republic|Tomtor]]. The station is at {{cvt|750|m|ft}} above [[sea level]] and the surrounding mountains at {{cvt|1100|m|ft}}, causing cold air to pool in the valley: in fact, recent studies show that winter temperatures in the area ''increase'' with altitude by as much as {{convert|10|C-change}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igsoc.org/annals/v52/58/a58A068.pdf |title=International Glaciological Society (IGS) |publisher=Igsoc.org |date=2012-02-13 |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome years the temperature drops below {{convert|0|C|0}} in late September and may remain below freezing until mid-April. In Oymyakon sometimes the average minimum temperature for December, January, and February remains below {{convert|-50|C|0}}. Sometimes summer months can also be quite cold, but June and July are the only months where the temperature has never dropped below {{convert|-10|C|0}}. Oymyakon and Verkhoyansk are the only two permanently inhabited places in the world that have recorded temperatures below {{convert|-60.0|C|0}} for every day in January.<ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24688&month=1&year=2013 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"climate-verkhoyansk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24266&month=1&year=2013 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0435 |publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOymyakon has never recorded an above-freezing temperature between October 25 and March 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24688&month=10&year=2013 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogodaiklimat.ru |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough winters in Oymyakon are long and extremely cold, summers are mild to warm, sometimes hot.\nThe warmest month on record is July 2010 with an average temperature of {{convert|+18.7|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/monitor.php?id=24688&month=7&year=2010|title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogoda.ru.net |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> In June, July and August temperatures over {{convert|30|C|0}} are not rare during the day. On July 28,&nbsp;2010, Oymyakon recorded a record high temperature of {{convert|34.6|C|0}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pogoda.ru.net/monitor.php?id=24688&month=7&year=2010 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442 - \u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440: \u043f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041e\u0439\u043c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435 |publisher=Pogoda.ru.net |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref> yielding a temperature range of {{convert|102.3|C-change}}. [[Verkhoyansk]] and [[Yakutsk]] are the only other known places in the world that have a temperature amplitude higher than {{convert|100|C-change}}.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nThe climate is quite dry, but as average monthly temperatures are below freezing for seven months of the year, substantial evaporation occurs only in summer months. Summers are much wetter than winters.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location=Oymyakon (1981\u20132010), extremes 1891\u2013present\n|metric first= yes\n|single line=yes\n|Jan record high C = \u221216.6\n|Feb record high C = \u221212.5\n|Mar record high C = 2.0\n|Apr record high C = 11.7\n|May record high C = 26.2\n|Jun record high C = 31.1\n|Jul record high C = 34.6\n|Aug record high C = 33.1\n|Sep record high C = 23.7\n|Oct record high C = 11.0\n|Nov record high C = \u22122.1\n|Dec record high C = \u22126.5\n|year record high C = 34.6\n|Jan high C = \u221243.0\n|Feb high C = \u221235.7\n|Mar high C = \u221220.8\n|Apr high C = \u22123.7\n|May high C = 9.1\n|Jun high C = 20.0\n|Jul high C = 22.7\n|Aug high C = 18.1\n|Sep high C = 8.9\n|Oct high C = \u22129.2\n|Nov high C = \u221231.0\n|Dec high C = \u221242.4\n|year high C = \u22128.9\n|Jan mean C = \u221246.4\n|Feb mean C = \u221242.0\n|Mar mean C = \u221231.2\n|Apr mean C = \u221213.6\n|May mean C = 2.7\n|Jun mean C = 12.6\n|Jul mean C = 14.9\n|Aug mean C = 10.3\n|Sep mean C = 2.3\n|Oct mean C = \u221214.